[[sn:Ancient Japanese Census Registration System]] [[ja:古代日本の戸籍制度]]

'''Ancient Japanese Census Registration System''' (古代日本の戸籍制度, Kodai Nihon no Koseki Seido) refers to the census registration system established during the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=|12=draft}} for population management. Notable examples include the {{ill|Kōgo Census|ja|庚午年籍|qq=|12=draft}} (670 AD) and the {{ill|Kōin Census|ja|庚寅年籍|qq=|12=draft}} (690 AD). Some portions of these ancient census records survive as part of the {{ill|Shōsōin documents|ja|正倉院文書|qq=|12=draft}}, while other records have been uncovered as {{ill|lacquered paper documents|ja|漆紙文書|qq=|12=draft}} at sites such as the {{ill|Akita Castle|ja|秋田城跡|qq=|12=draft}} and {{ill|Tagajō|ja|多賀城跡|qq=|12=draft}}, as well as in the form of wooden tablets (木簡) in provincial locations like the {{ill|Suō Province|ja|周防国|qq=|12=draft}} capital. Advances in infrared analysis have facilitated the deciphering of these records. The Kōgo Census, compiled in 670 AD (the 9th year of Emperor Tenji's reign), marked Japan's first nationwide census. Although census records were typically destroyed after 30 years, the Kōgo Census was designated for permanent preservation. This census coincided with the enforcement of the {{ill|Ōmi Code|ja|近江令|qq=|12=draft}}, reflecting its legal framework. == The Beginnings of Census Records == Early mentions of census compilation appear in: * '''540 AD (Emperor Kinmei's reign):''' "Foreigners such as Qin and Han people, settled in the regions and listed in census registers." This indicates that census registration initially focused on managing immigrant populations.<ref>{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=|12=draft}}</ref> * '''569 AD:''' Emperor Kinmei ordered inspections of tax registries in the {{ill|Shirai no Miyake|ja|白猪屯倉|1=Shirai no Miyake|qq=|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Kibi Province|ja|吉備国|qq=|12=draft}} to ensure proper registration of taxable individuals. * '''574 AD:''' {{ill|Soga no Umako|ja|蘇我馬子|qq=|12=draft}} increased census efforts in Kibi, refining population control in granary-associated labor. These efforts primarily targeted immigrants and administrative groups such as granary laborers, differing from the comprehensive population control established under the Ritsuryō system. == Kōgo Census == The {{ill|Kōgo Census|ja|庚午年籍|qq=|12=draft}} was compiled in 670 AD to implement the reforms proposed by the {{ill|Taika Reforms|ja|大化の改新|qq=|12=draft}}. It represented Japan's first comprehensive national census, covering areas from {{ill|Kyūshū|ja|九州|qq=|12=draft}} to {{ill|Kantō|ja|関東|qq=|12=draft}}. However, the original records are no longer extant, and questions remain about whether all societal classes were included. Subsequent records and lawsuits involving surname changes or social status disputes, however, demonstrate its use as a foundational document. The Kōgo Census was copied and stored in the central government archives until the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=|12=draft}}. == Kōin Census == The {{ill|Kōin Census|ja|庚寅年籍|qq=|12=draft}}, compiled in 690 AD under the {{ill|Asuka Kiyomihara Code|ja|飛鳥浄御原令|qq=|12=draft}}, represented the next stage in census development. It detailed all households and individuals, enabling the implementation of the {{ill|Handen-Shūju System|ja|班田収授法|qq=|12=draft}} and comprehensive tax collection. == Census Records and Reused Documents == Due to the high value of paper in ancient Japan, discarded census records were often reused by temples and government offices for other purposes. Many such reused documents, now known as {{ill|Recycled Paper Documents|ja|紙背文書|qq=|12=draft}}, have been preserved in collections such as the {{ill|Shōsōin|ja|正倉院|qq=|12=draft}}. == Conclusion == The comprehensive compilation of census records continued until the mid-10th century but declined as the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=|12=draft}} weakened. The establishment of the {{ill|Shōen system|ja|荘園制|qq=|12=draft}} reduced the need for centralized population management, marking the end of systematic census compilation. == Related Chronology == - 540 AD: Census registration of immigrant groups. - 670 AD: Compilation of the Kōgo Census. - 690 AD: Compilation of the Kōin Census under the Asuka Kiyomihara Code. - 702 AD: The oldest surviving census, the {{ill|Hanpurī Census|ja|半布里戸籍|qq=|12=draft}}, was compiled. == References == <references/> == Further Reading == * {{Cite journal|author=Atsushi Nito |title=Research on Shōsōin Documents |journal=National Museum of Japanese History Bulletin |date=2014-12 |volume=192 |pages=57–64 |url=https://doi.org/10.15024/00002189|qq=}} == See Also == * {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=|12=draft}} * {{ill|Handen-Shūju System|ja|班田収授法|qq=|12=draft}} * {{ill|Ancient Japanese Provincial Administration|ja|古代日本の地方官制|qq=|12=draft}} * {{ill|Census Records|ja|計帳|qq=|12=draft}}
