Some portions of these ancient census records survive as part of the {{ill|Shōsōin documents|ja|正倉院文書|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, while other records have been uncovered as {{ill|lacquered paper documents|ja|漆紙文書|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} at sites such as the {{ill|Akita Castle|ja|秋田城跡|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Tagajō|ja|多賀城跡|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, as well as in the form of wooden tablets (木簡) in provincial locations like the {{ill|Suō Province|ja|周防国|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} capital. Advances in infrared analysis have facilitated the deciphering of these records.
The Kōgo Census, compiled in 670 AD (the 9th year of Emperor Tenji's reign), marked Japan's first nationwide census. Although census records were typically destroyed after 30 years, the Kōgo Census was designated for permanent preservation. This census coincided with the enforcement of the {{ill|Ōmi Code|ja|近江令|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, reflecting its legal framework.
