'''Ancient Japanese Census Registration System''' (古代日本の戸籍制度, Kodai Nihon no Koseki Seido) refers to the census registration system established during the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} for population management. Notable examples include the {{ill|Kōgo Census|ja|庚午年籍|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (670 AD) and the {{ill|Kōin Census|ja|庚寅年籍|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (690 AD). Some portions of these ancient census records survive as part of the {{ill|Shōsōin documents|ja|正倉院文書|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, while other records have been uncovered as {{ill|lacquered paper documents|ja|漆紙文書|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} at sites such as the {{ill|Akita Castle|ja|秋田城跡|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Tagajō|ja|多賀城跡|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, as well as in the form of wooden tablets (木簡) in provincial locations like the {{ill|Suō Province|ja|周防国|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} capital. Advances in infrared analysis have facilitated the deciphering of these records. The Kōgo Census, compiled in 670 AD (the 9th year of Emperor Tenji's reign), marked Japan's first nationwide census. Although census records were typically destroyed after 30 years, the Kōgo Census was designated for permanent preservation. This census coincided with the enforcement of the {{ill|Ōmi Code|ja|近江令|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, reflecting its legal framework. == The Beginnings of Census Records == Early mentions of census compilation appear in: * '''540 AD (Emperor Kinmei's reign):''' "Foreigners such as Qin and Han people, settled in the regions and listed in census registers." This indicates that census registration initially focused on managing immigrant populations.<ref>{{ill|Nihon Sho